Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Put the sweet potato chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, sprinkle over half the @Indonesian style spice mix{2%sachets}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Zest and cut the @lime{1} into wedges. Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

In a #large saucepan{}, combine the @peanut butter{30%g}, @sambal paste{15%g}, @ketjap manis{25%g}, @Hot Water{2%tbsp}(for the sauce) and the remaining Indonesian style spice mix.

Mix well until smooth.

> TIP: If your peanut butter has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} to the pan. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw meat.

Pop the #saucepan{} on medium-high heat and gradually stir in the browned chicken, @coconut milk{180%ml}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{50%ml}(for the sauce), then bring to the boil.

Simmer, stirring constantly, until thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}. Remove from the heat, then stir in half the lime juice and season with @salt{}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so there's no pink in the middle of the chicken.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, pop the satay pan back on medium heat and stir in the sweet potato.

Add the @peas{120%g} to the pan and simmer until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}, then remove from the heat.

Taste and season with more salt and lime juice if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, stir through the lime zest then share out between your #serving bowls{}.

Spoon the chicken satay curry over the zesty rice and finish with a sprinkling of peanuts.

Serve any remaining lime wedges on the side for squeezing over.

Enjoy!